entry.title: Let MemoryManagedPaintCanvas keep track of pinned images
entry.content:
The MemoryManagedPaintCanvas class had a callback mechanism allowing

clients to be notified whenever images are recorded in the canvas. The

goal was to keep track of the total amount of memory consumed by images.



A follow up CL will split the recording in two: a main recording, and a

side recording that stores the content of unclosed layers. The main

recording can always be flushed, but not the side recording. We will

have to keep track of image memory pinned in both recordings. The simple

way to do this is to have the MemoryManagedPaintCanvas class itself keep

track of memory usage.

entry.title: Revert "Recalculate style before setting ICB size for printing."
entry.content:
This reverts commit f992984634e8ffc2a9faba835da87085d7a79916.



Reason for revert: Causing PrintBrowserTest.NoResizeEvent to fail on Linux. Example build: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20ChromiumOS%20MSan%20Tests/38907/overview



Original change's description:

> Recalculate style before setting ICB size for printing.

>

> A zoom factor used when viewing a webpage on screen may have been set in

> computed style. This would affect @page margin resolution incorrectly

> when entering print mode, which in turn would result in an incorrect

> initial containing block size. To fix this, recalculate style before

> calculating the page area size.

>

> Since we now recalculate style before setting any initial containing

> block size for printing at all, viewport units will not be resolved

> correctly. So make sure that they get calculated before laying out. This

> used to be triggered by calling LayoutViewportWasResized(). It turns out

> though, now that we need to do this unconditionally before the first

> layout, that LayoutViewportWasResized() does more than we want. For

> printing, we don't need to re-evaluate media queries, and we do not want

> a resize event to be fired. Therefore, split the viewport units dirtying

> into a separate function. Introduce a lambda in

> ForceLayoutForPagination() to avoid repetitive code.

>

> Make PrintBrowserTest.NoResizeEvent more evil, by modifying its resource

> HTML file to use a named page, and also a wide DIV. This would make the

> test fail without this CL.

>

> Add external/wpt/css/printing/ to the scalefactor200 virtual test suite.

> Three other tests (the already existing page-margin-xxx tests) would

> also fail without this fix, but add a test for this specific issue

> (abspos) as well.

>

entry.title: [Autofill] Weaken CHECKs for contenteditable
entry.content:
The parameters of Get{Form,Field}RendererId() have been changed

from WebForm[Control]Element to WebElement for contenteditable

support.



The DCHECKs in these functions were supposed to compensate for the

loss of type safety. They essentially checked that the argument is

a WebForm[Control]Element or a contenteditable. But a former

contenteditable can become a non-contenteditable. We might easily

hit the DCHECK in such cases. Those cases don't see too dangerous

because the contract of FindFormForContentEditable() excludes

non-contenteditables, i.e., any caller must check the element

accordingly.



Therefore, this CL replaces the DCHECKs with CHECKs that just

ensure the argument is not a WebFormControlElement or

WebFormElement, respectively. This should suffice to protect

against mixups of Get{Form,Field}RendererId() in most cases.

entry.title: [TabStripPerformance] Fix incorrect positioning on startup
entry.content:
Fix incorrect positioning on startup.

-Fixes when the active tab will be the first on the strip.

-Fixes when the new tab page start surface will be shown.



The issue stemmed from replacing the tabs at incorrect indices during the placeholder flow. When the tab state was initialized, we would update the layout once more, but this would not result in the correct positioning. The missing tabs would be correctly created here [1], have incorrect positions calculated here (as widths were still 0) [2], and have the widths set here [3]. Another layout would be required to resolve this. I opted to instead replace the correct placeholders, so no tabs would be missing during this final layout, thus sidestepping this issue.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/android/java/src/org/chromium/chrome/browser/compositor/overlays/strip/StripLayoutHelper.java;l=2024;drc=f5bdc89c7395ed24f1b8d196a3bdd6232d5bf771

[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/android/java/src/org/chromium/chrome/browser/compositor/overlays/strip/StripLayoutHelper.java;l=2031;drc=f5bdc89c7395ed24f1b8d196a3bdd6232d5bf771

[3] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/android/java/src/org/chromium/chrome/browser/compositor/overlays/strip/StripLayoutHelper.java;l=2034-2035;drc=f5bdc89c7395ed24f1b8d196a3bdd6232d5bf771

entry.title: [soft-navigations] Fix navigations invariants crash
entry.content:
With soft navigations, we pass along a task ID when a renderer initiated

a history navigation. Then when receiving that ID when creating a new

NavigationRequest, we verify that the navigation is indeed a same

document navigation.



It turns out that on restored sessions, same-document history

navigations did not have a type that distinguishes them from

cross-document restored navigation, resulting in a DCHECK failure.



This CL adds this new type, and modifies the DCHECK to take it into

consideration.

entry.title: Protected Audiences: Cache loaded interest groups
entry.content:
Loading interest groups is slow, and they are loaded for each auction and component auction on a page. A cache for interest group loading can speed up the auction by removing repetitive loads.



This change introduces a new class, InterestGroupCachingStorage which wraps around InterestGroupStorage and provides access to an owner's interest groups that are already in memory if available instead of loading them from the database each time (it also handles cache invalidation when values are changed).



The new class is not yet used anywhere. In a following change, InterestGroupCachingStorage will be used by the InterestGroupManager in place of InterestGroupStorage.

entry.title: Add whitespace around AtomicInline layout objects when computing AccName
entry.content:
While not formalized in the AccName spec yet, there are discussions about adding white-space around inline-block elements.



- https://github.com/w3c/accname/issues/205

- https://github.com/w3c/accname/issues/15

- https://github.com/w3c/accname/issues/3



This change will make Chromium add whitespace around inline-block, inline-grid, inline-table, and inline-flex elements when computing Name from Content. This will let us pass the WPT tests that are in progress of being written: https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/42354



Notes:



- The WPT tests only mention inline-block, and there is no mention of the other inline-* properties yet. I think it's OK that this patch adds whitespace around other inline-* display properties (probably moreso than inline-block) because those properties define special formatting rules for their children, but let me know if you disagree and I can special-case this logic for inline-block.



- It seems that elements have an AtomicInline display type, similar to the other inline-* display types. This means that we start outputting whitespace around elements when computing name from content as well. This feels fine, but as before, let me know if you disagree and I can hardcode what cases are OK. (As an aside, something seems broken with Name from Content when children are MathML? It's preexisting, and should probably be fixed in another CL)

the given {Form,Field}RendererId refers to a form [control] element or

a contenteditable. For example, that's what ExtractForm(FormRendererId)

from crrev.com/c/4915629 does.

entry.title: [Tab Switcher] Ensure setOnNextLayoutRunnable will always play
entry.content:
The runnable set via setOnNextLayoutRunnable might not run if onLayout

isn't called. This can happen if there are no changes to layout

dimension. When this happens the animation may not start leaving the UI

in a bad state. Fix this by posting the runnable to happen at the end of

the UI thread queue. Either:



1) The layout will happen before the posted task and the posted task

will no-op.

2) The layout didn't happen (it should have been queued already) this

means the layout didn't happen (likely no change) so the runnable

should be run immediately.
